const MODERN_PROSE_01 = `The estate had its own weather. That was what Lena noticed first when they moved in — not the graffiti on the stairwells or the lifts that smelled of something she didn't want to identify, but the way the wind behaved differently here, channelled and accelerated by the tower blocks into corridors of cold air that hit you side-on and made your eyes water.

Their flat was on the fourteenth floor. From the kitchen window, Lena could see the whole city laid out like a circuit board — the lights, the roads, the dark rectangles of parks. It was beautiful, she told herself, if you didn't look down. Looking down meant the car park where the older boys gathered after dark, the playground where the swings had been removed after someone got stabbed, the patch of grass that the council had stopped mowing in what Lena's mother called "an act of administrative surrender."

Lena's mother was a woman who cleaned other people's offices from six in the morning until two in the afternoon, then came home and cleaned her own flat until it shone like a rebuke. She believed in bleach the way other people believed in prayer — as a force that could purify, protect, and hold the chaos at bay. The flat was spotless. The windows gleamed. The line between inside and outside was maintained with a vigilance that Lena understood, even at fourteen, was not really about cleaning at all.

"This estate is not us," her mother said, every time Lena complained. "We live here. We are not from here. There is a difference."

Lena was not sure there was.`

