const MODERN_PROSE_02 = `The letter arrived on a Thursday, which felt wrong. Important letters should arrive on Mondays, Daniel thought — the start of something, a clean break in the week. Thursdays were for coasting, for letting the momentum of the week carry you toward the weekend. Thursdays were not for being told that the company you had worked for since you were twenty-three was "restructuring its operational model" and that your position had been "identified for redundancy."

He read it three times. The language was extraordinary — not cruel, exactly, but evasive in a way that felt worse than cruelty. Nowhere did it say: we are firing you. It said "regrettably" and "following a comprehensive review" and "we appreciate your contribution." His contribution. Twenty-two years of Monday mornings and Tuesday afternoons and Wednesday lunch breaks spent at the same desk, eating the same sandwich, looking at the same car park through the same window. His contribution.

Daniel folded the letter carefully and put it in his jacket pocket. He made tea. He drank the tea. He washed the mug and placed it upside down on the draining board, exactly as he did every morning, because routine was the last honest thing he had.

He did not tell Margaret until Sunday. He spent the intervening days going to work as usual, driving the same route, parking in the same space, sitting at his desk and performing the motions of a job that no longer existed, and he discovered something unexpected: that pretending to be employed felt almost identical to being employed, and that this similarity was the most frightening thing he had ever encountered.`

