const C19_PROSE_02 = `The schoolroom was cold, as it always was, and the fire — which Mr Thornton permitted between the hours of eleven and two on weekdays only — had not yet been lit. The children sat in rows, their hands tucked beneath them for warmth, their breath visible in the grey morning air. There were forty-three of them, ranging in age from five to thirteen, and they shared between them twelve slates, three reading primers, and one globe of the world from which most of Africa and all of Australia had been rubbed away by generations of small, curious fingers.

Miss Hartley stood before them with the particular expression of someone who has been given an impossible task and intends to accomplish it anyway. She was twenty-four years old, the daughter of a clergyman who had died leaving more books than money, and she had been teaching in Mr Thornton's school for two years — long enough to know that the children learned despite the conditions rather than because of them, and that Mr Thornton's interest in education extended precisely as far as the charitable reputation it afforded him and not one inch further.

"Good morning, children."

"Good morning, Miss Hartley."

Their voices rose in the cold air like something released. Miss Hartley allowed herself, very briefly, to feel the thing she tried not to feel too often: that these children deserved better, that she was not enough, and that the distance between what they needed and what she could provide was a space she would spend her whole life trying to cross and never quite manage.

She opened the primer. "Today," she said, with a brightness she did not feel, "we shall begin with reading."`

