              'Grade 6-7': 'Shakespeare dramatises Macbeth\'s moral conflict through a soliloquy structured as a formal argument against murder that paradoxically reveals the depth of his temptation. The opening clause — "If it were done when \'tis done, then \'twere well / It were done quickly" — is a tangle of conditionals that linguistically enacts moral confusion. The repetition of "done" creates a circular, trapped quality, and the qualifying "if" reveals that Macbeth\'s primary concern is not whether to act but whether the act can be contained — "trammel up the consequence." The fishing metaphor of "trammel" positions murder as an attempt to net and control consequences that are, by their nature, uncontainable. The "poisoned chalice" image operates on multiple levels: the communion chalice connects regicide to sacrilege, and the poison that returns "to our own lips" establishes the principle of moral reciprocity. The tripartite listing of obligations — "kinsman," "subject," "host" — creates an escalating structure where each relationship adds a further layer of prohibition. Shakespeare gives Macbeth complete moral clarity about why the murder is wrong, which makes his eventual decision more disturbing: it is not ignorance but knowledge that is overridden. The soliloquy\'s absence of Lady Macbeth or the witches is crucial — here, Macbeth confronts the moral case alone and finds it overwhelming, revealing that his moral conscience is intact even as his ambition prepares to override it.',
