            modelAnswers: {
              'Grade 4-5': 'The writer presents Daniel as shocked and struggling to process his redundancy. He objects to the letter arriving on a Thursday rather than Monday, which shows he is focusing on a small detail to avoid the bigger truth. The corporate language bothers him — phrases like "restructuring its operational model" avoid saying "we are firing you." His reaction is surprisingly calm — he folds the letter, makes tea, washes the mug — showing he retreats into routine when faced with crisis. The most significant detail is that he continues going to work for three days without telling his wife, pretending nothing has changed. The writer says he discovers that "pretending to be employed felt almost identical to being employed," which is a frightening idea about how much of working life is just going through motions.',
              'Grade 6-7': 'The writer constructs Daniel\'s response to redundancy as a study in the relationship between routine, identity, and self-deception. The opening objection to Thursday — an absurdly specific grievance — is both comic and psychologically acute: Daniel displaces his distress onto a trivial detail because the significant detail (his dismissal) is too large to process. The letter\'s corporate language is dissected with quiet fury: "restructuring its operational model" and "identified for redundancy" use passive constructions that erase human agency, and Daniel\'s internal correction — nowhere does it say "we are firing you" — exposes the gap between institutional language and human reality. His post-letter routine (folding, tea, washing, draining board) is presented with meticulous specificity that mirrors Daniel\'s own meticulousness. The sentence "routine was the last honest thing he had" is the extract\'s most revealing: it identifies routine as the only remaining form of authenticity, which is paradoxical because routine is by definition the opposite of spontaneous, authentic experience. The three days of continued attendance at a non-existent job constitute the extract\'s most psychologically complex episode. The discovery that "pretending to be employed felt almost identical to being employed" is devastating because it retroactively contaminates his entire career: if the performance of work is indistinguishable from work, then the twenty-two years were themselves a kind of performance. Daniel\'s refusal to tell Margaret transforms private knowledge into private burden, and the delay until Sunday suggests he is waiting for the week to reset, as though a new week might somehow neutralise Thursday\'s letter.',
              'Grade 8-9': 'The writer presents Daniel\'s response to redundancy as an existential crisis disguised as administrative inconvenience, using the gap between institutional language and lived experience to expose the fragility of work-based identity. The Thursday objection is not merely comic displacement but an attempt to preserve the categorical order that the letter has disrupted: Mondays are for beginnings, Thursdays are for "coasting," and a redundancy letter on a Thursday is, in Daniel\'s taxonomy, a procedural violation. This instinct — to critique the process rather than confront the content — is the first indication that Daniel\'s identity is invested in systems and routines rather than in autonomous selfhood. The letter\'s language is subjected to analysis that doubles as the extract\'s most trenchant social critique. "Restructuring its operational model" transforms a human decision (to fire people) into a mechanical adjustment (to restructure a model), and "identified for redundancy" positions Daniel as an object found by a process rather than a person affected by a choice. His sardonic inventory of twenty-two years — "Monday mornings and Tuesday afternoons and Wednesday lunch breaks" — reduces a career to temporal units, stripping it of content and leaving only duration. The post-letter routine (fold, tea, wash, drain) is both coping mechanism and revelation: if "routine was the last honest thing he had," then the routine was always the primary content of his working life, and the work itself was secondary. The three-day performance of continued employment is the extract\'s philosophical centre. The discovery that pretending and working are "almost identical" functions as an inadvertent phenomenological insight: it suggests that modern employment is already a form of performance, a daily enactment of identity through repetitive physical and spatial practices (same route, same space, same desk) that do not require the work to be real. Daniel\'s fear — that this similarity is "the most frightening thing he had ever encountered" — is the moment where administrative crisis becomes existential crisis: if work and its performance are indistinguishable, then the self that was constructed through twenty-two years of employment may itself be a performance, and redundancy has not merely ended his job but exposed its (and his) ontological emptiness.',
            },
